<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: MANHATTAN BEACH; $32.8-MILLION BUDGET IS OKD BY COUNCIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES BENNING 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Manhattan Beach will spend about $2.8 million on capital improvements next 
year that include $250,000 in work to the city's pier and $100,000 in 
improvements to tennis courts at Mira Costa High School. 
</P>
<P>
 The improvements are included in a $32.8-million budget unanimously approved 
by the City Council this week for fiscal year 1994-95.The new budget is about 
1% more than last year's budget. 
</P>
<P>
 The city anticipates that revenues will decline by about $1 million next year, 
mainly as a result of cuts in federal transportation funds. But an increase in 
property tax revenues last year will help offset the decline. 
</P>
<P>
 Several positions that were eliminated through attrition last year when the 
city's Department of Public Works was reorganized will not be replaced under 
the new budget. 
</P>
<P>
 The budget includes a general fund reserve of $3.2 million. JAMES BENNING 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
