<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: FORMER HOSPITAL PATIENT RETURNS TO HELP LIFT THE SPIRITS OF OTHERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN PATERNO, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When Steven Dimmick burned his little toe on a campfire a few years ago, he 
never thought it would lead to gangrene, a partial amputation of his foot, 
impaired eyesight and five months in the hospital. But as much as he lost in 
the experience, Dimmick found something too: humanity. 
</P>
<P>
 During his 1992 stay at Robert F. Kennedy Medical Center in Hawthorne, he 
spent a good deal of time helping other patients cope with depression. Dimmick, 
29, is still on the road to recovery, but he continues to spend three and four 
days a week on the hospital's third floor, helping lift the spirits of those 
who need it. 
</P>
<P>
 Dimmick says he helps himself feel better by helping others. He gets the guy 
in traction a banana that the nurses don't have time to fetch. He plays cards. 
He talks. He offers suggestions -- based on his own experiences -- on how to 
cope with the long hospital days and nights. 
</P>
<P>
 "Steve is wonderful," said Julia Johnson, director of activities for the 
hospital recreational therapy program on the third floor. "He's so loving, 
warmhearted and caring. He gives a lot of himself to patients and to the staff. 
He's always there to assist us." 
</P>
<P>
 She said the other patients feel comfortable with him. "They feel his 
kindness. He gives them a little extra tender loving care, a little extra time. 
That makes them feel good about themselves. Just being there to share with the 
other patients and letting them know, 'Hey, you're not alone. I've been going 
through it for years.' That's a good feeling." 
</P>
<P>
 Dimmick, who lives in Gardena, calls the hospital his "home away from home." 
His eyes fill with tears when he remembers the day he was discharged. "That 
staff did so much for me," he said. "I wanted to return the favor." 
</P>
<P>
 Hospitals were the furthest thing from his mind in December, 1991, when he 
burned his toe. He and his friends were sitting around the campfire, drinking 
and talking, when he casually moved a metal lawn chair with his bare foot. He 
didn't realize the chair had been close to the fire and the metal was hot 
enough to burn his skin. 
</P>
<P>
 A diabetic since age 11, Dimmick knew how important it was to make sure the 
wound healed. Because of blood sugar imbalances, diabetics are much more 
susceptible to chronic infection and eventual gangrene than are non-diabetics, 
he explained. "But I wasn't too worried," he said, because he had previously 
had numerous scrapes, burns and blisters without problems. 
</P>
<P>
 A few days later, the blister was nearly gone. Then Dimmick got the flu. For 
five days, he lay in bed, not even feeling well enough to take off his socks. 
When he did, he was horror-stricken: Nearly half of his left foot was black.  
</P>
<P>
 "I was hoping my brother had played a practical joke on me," he said. "I 
yelled at him, 'Please tell me you painted my foot black, please tell me!' But 
he said he hadn't. 
</P>
<P>
 "I never thought this could happen to me, especially from a little blister." 
</P>
<P>
 Despite more than a dozen surgeries, Dimmick lost only a small part of his 
foot. And although his eyesight was damaged because of a complication of the 
diabetes, he has regained most of his sight. He is learning to walk again and 
hopes to go back someday to his job as a union carpenter. 
</P>
<P>
 "If I had to do it all over again, I'd probably become a doctor," he said. "In 
my work, I can finish building something and say, 'I built that,' and it's a 
neat feeling. But it's not the same as seeing people feel better or look 
better. I get more satisfaction from seeing people laugh."  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Nancy Haruye Au of Manhattan Beach was one of 10 Los Angeles-area women 
honored by the County Commission for Women for her work with poor women and 
families. Au is the executive director of two counseling agencies, the 
Assistance League of Southern California's Family Service Agency and the 
Western Region Asian Pacific Agency.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Redondo Beach resident Catherine M. Gates, a senior at the University of the 
Pacific in Stockton, won the Bernays Cup, a national writing competition for 
public relations students. Gates is majoring in communications.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Playa del Rey resident Omar S. Es-Said, associate professor of mechanical 
engineering at Loyola Marymount University, was named an outstanding 
engineering educator by the Society of Automotive Engineers. Es-Said was one of 
21 winners chosen from a nationwide field. * 
</P>
<P>
 Westchester resident Laura Bayne was elected the Los Angeles/Long Beach area 
Toastmasters International lieutenant governor of education and training. 
Toastmasters is a nonprofit educational organization formed to help people 
develop self-confidence through public speaking. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Inglewood resident Helen Jean Monteilh has been appointed to the Los Angeles 
County Historical Landmarks and Records Commission by Supervisor Yvonne 
Brathwaite Burke. Monteilh, a retired college professor, is also a member of 
the Inglewood Parks and Recreation Commission. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Carson middle school students Anna Adriana Gutierrez and Dave Sormillon won 
awards in the Cesar Chavez Essay/Poetry contest sponsored by the Los Angeles 
Unified School District. Gutierrez took top honors for her Spanish language 
essay in the middle school category. Sormillon won second place for his English 
language submission. Both students attend Stephen White Middle School and wrote 
on the topic "Cesar Chavez: The Benefits of His Work." The winners were chosen 
out of 450 entries from across the district. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Palos Verdes Peninsula Unified School District has selected new board 
liaisons. They are: Joan Davidson, liaison with Palos Verdes and Rolling Hills 
Estates; Barry Hildebrand, Rancho Palos Verdes and the Metropolitan 
Transportation Authority; Peter Gardiner, Rancho Palos Verdes and Rolling Hills 
Estates; Ellen Perkins, Rolling Hills and Rancho Palos Verdes Library District; 
Brent Goodrich, Rolling Hills, Palos Verdes Library District and the 
Metropolitan Transportation Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
