<TEXT>
<P>
 A Los Angeles County sheriff's deputy accused of sexually abusing his 
estranged wife's children was ordered to stand trial after waiving his right to 
a preliminary hearing.  
</P>
<P>
 Municipal Judge David Horowitz bound Darryl Erwin Byrd, who remains in custody 
in lieu of $375,000 bail, over for trial in Los Angeles Superior Court on two 
felony counts of continuous sexual abuse of a child. 
</P>
<P>
 Byrd also was ordered to stand trial on one unrelated felony count of unlawful 
storage of a firearm for an incident that ended in the death of a teen-age boy 
last Christmas Eve.  
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Public Defender Mark Zavidow said his client waived his right to a 
preliminary hearing "for reasons that make sense to us."  
</P>
<P>
 The public defender said the hearing would have been of little use to the 
defense because the prosecution was planning to present a "hearsay" hearing in 
which police officers testify about the contents of their reports. 
</P>
