<HEADLINE>
<P>
VATICAN, ISRAEL CEMENT FULL DIPLOMATIC TIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Israel and the Vatican established full diplomatic ties Wednesday and said 
ambassadors will be exchanged soon, sealing a historic accord on mutual 
recognition and reconciliation after centuries of bitterness between Roman 
Catholics and Jews. 
</P>
<P>
 Israeli Deputy Foreign Minister Yossi Beilin said he and Vatican envoy 
Archbishop Andrea Cordero Lanza di Montezemolo signed the relations agreement 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 The two sides had signed a 14-point "fundamental agreement" in December 
officially recognizing each other, but they delayed full ties until final 
details could be settled. 
</P>
<P>
 Beilin portrayed the pact as a fruit of Israel's peace accord with the 
Palestine Liberation Organization. The Vatican is the 41st state to either 
establish, renew or upgrade ties with Israel since Arab-Israeli peace 
negotiations began in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
 Beilin said the agreement recognizes the Vatican's right to have a say on the 
status of Jerusalem, especially the protection of holy sites. 
</P>
<P>
 He also said that one of the "important fruits" of the agreement will be a 
rare exhibition of the Dead Sea Scrolls on June 29 at the Vatican. He said the 
scrolls, discovered nearly 50 years ago, have never been displayed in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
 Two commissions of experts will now work out details of the legal and fiscal 
status of the Catholic Church and its possessions in the Holy Land, Beilin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Vatican will open its embassy in Jaffa, a former Arab town that is now 
part of Tel Aviv and has a sizable Christian Arab population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
