<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: ENERGY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 OPEC Leaves Production Quotas Unchanged: Believing it has found the key to 
higher prices, the cartel left untouched its crude production levels for the 
rest of 1994. In adopting a hands-off policy, the Organization of Petroleum 
Exporting Countries is gambling that oil prices will continue rallying in the 
fall and winter, with increased demand for crude in the United States and 
elsewhere.Oil prices tumbled late last year to their lowest levels in five 
years. But since the cartel agreed in March to cap its output at 24.5 million 
barrels a day through the end of the year, the price of the U.S. benchmark 
grade of oil has gained more than $5 a barrel. Crude oil prices rose sharply 
Wednesday, reaching their highest level in more than a year and flirting with 
the $20-a-barrel mark. 
</P>
