<HEADLINE>
<P>
GLENDALE / BURBANK FOCUS: GLENDALE; MAYOR NAMES PANEL TO PROBE HATE CRIME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JENNIFER OLDHAM 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Glendale Mayor Eileen Givens announced this week the members of a Community 
Relations Task Force formed at the request of local Armenian groups to 
investigate a hate crime at an Armenian-American youth center last month. 
</P>
<P>
 The task force will meet several times, with its first meeting scheduled in 
the next two weeks, Givens said. 
</P>
<P>
 The committee is charged with recommending ways the community can "work 
together to encourage intercultural understanding," Givens said. 
</P>
<P>
 Local Armenian groups called for the City Council to nominate a committee to 
study the May 14 vandalism of the Homenetmen Armenian General Athletics Union 
and Scouts Building at 544 W. Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
 Vandals painted swastikas on the building's walls and on several vans parked 
nearby. Police have no suspects. 
</P>
<P>
 The vandalism set off a round of insults aimed at Armenians by other residents 
who claimed Armenian immigrants, who make up about 20% of Glendale's 195,000 
residents, were asking for special treatment from city officials. 
</P>
<P>
 The task force will include Pierre Chraghchian, a Homenetmen board member; 
Mayor Eileen Givens; Mary Hamilton, former Chamber of Commerce president; Susan 
Hunt, president of the Glendale Council PTA; Chahe Keuroghelian, intercultural 
relations coordinator for the Glendale Police Department; Harry Kimm, an 
interpreter with the Stanford International Group, and Karen La Madrid, 
associate general counsel, Department of Legal Affairs, Southern California 
Assn. of Seventh-day Adventists. 
</P>
<P>
 Also: Angus MacLeod, past president of the Glendale Council on Aging; Rabbi 
Carole Meyers, head of Temple Sinai of Glendale; Alice Petrossian, director of 
special projects/intercultural education for the Glendale Unified School 
District; Frank Quintero, a member of the Arroyo Verdugo Sub-Regional Planning 
Committee; Glendale City Manager Dave Ramsay; Herman Sillas, an attorney with 
Ochoa & Sillas, and the Rev. Phil Wood, senior pastor, First United Methodist 
Church, Glendale. JENNIFER OLDHAM 
</P>
</TEXT>
